<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,787,1370,1736]" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Haec species a congeneris foliorum petiolo rhachideque indumento aureobrunneo tomentulosis, foliolis 6 ad 8 in sicco complanatis apice acute acuminatis, pedicellis c. 1 mm longis atque antheris 2.2-2.5 mm longis distinguitur.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="47" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,787,1776,1928]" lastBlockId="2.[824,1475,282,914]" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis box="[174,218,1776,1799]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Tree</emphasis>
c. 15 m tall; stems densely golden brown tomentulose. Petioles 2.6-4 cm, densely golden brown tomentulose. 
<emphasis box="[717,786,1808,1831]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Leaves</emphasis>
with 6-8 subopposite to alternate leaflets; rachis 3.8-7 cm, keeled above, golden brown tomentulose; petiolule 2.5-3 mm, golden brown tomentulose; leaflet blade 2.8-7 × 1.2-2.2 cm, elliptic, papyraceous to subcoriaceous, flat in pressed material, glabrous and only slightly glossy above, sparsely light brown tomentulose on midvein and secondary veins below, base weakly to markedly asymmetrical, acute to nearly decurrent, margins minutely thickened, not revolute, apex distinctly acuminate, the acumen acute, midvein distinctly raised and knife-like above and below, secondary veins (8-)10-13 per side, flat to slightly impressed above, raised below, tertiary venation obscure above, slightly raised and evident below. 
<emphasis box="[824,944,570,594]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Inflorescence</emphasis>
axis 16-19 cm long, c. 1 mm in diam., unbranched, dark chocolate brown, densely golden brown tomentulose; bracts c. 1 mm, narrowly triangular, adaxially concave; pedicels c. 1 mm, c. 0.8 mm in diam., densely golden brown tomentulose. 
<emphasis box="[903,1040,698,722]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Male flowers</emphasis>
with a shallowly cupulate, (4-)5-lobed calyx, the lobes broadly triangular, c. 1 × 1.2 mm, acute, densely golden brown tomentulose outside, densely golden setaceous inside; stamens 8, filaments 1-3 mm, glabrous, anthers 2.2-2.5 × c. 0.8 mm, ellipsoid; disc and pistillode densely golden setaceous, the trichomes to 0.5 mm. 
<emphasis box="[1166,1314,858,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Female flowers</emphasis>
not seen. 
<emphasis box="[1420,1474,859,882]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Fruit</emphasis>
not seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="47" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="2.[824,1474,954,1202]" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis box="[862,1060,955,978]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Conservation status</emphasis>
. – Known only from a single collection from well within an intact forest block of the newly designated Corridor Ankeniheny Zahamena PA (
<figureCitation box="[1229,1290,1018,1042]" captionStart="Fig. 3" captionStartId="5.[113,140,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[113,763,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[113,763,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. – Geographic distribution of Begueo onkeronensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (square), B. oustrolis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. betomponensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangle), B. golokensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (star) and B. vulgoris G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (circles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888181/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), and lacking any additional information on population size, 
<taxonomicName box="[1290,1450,1050,1074]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anteranensis">
<emphasis box="[1290,1450,1050,1074]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">B. ankeranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is assigned a provisional status of “Least Concern” [LC] using the IUCN Red List Criteria (
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" box="[1141,1281,1114,1138]" firstAuthor="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge" pageId="2" pageNumber="47" refId="ref13043" refString="IUCN (2012). IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed. IUCN Species Survival Commission, Gland &amp; Cambridge." title="IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria: Version 3.1. 2 nd ed." type="book" year="2012">IUCN, 2012</bibRefCitation>
), with the caution that this status is highly dependent on continued effective protection.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="47" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[824,1474,1242,1554]" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis box="[862,918,1243,1266]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Notes</emphasis>
. – 
<taxonomicName box="[951,1160,1242,1266]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anteranensis">
<emphasis box="[951,1160,1242,1266]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Beguea ankeranensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the type collection in humid forest at Ankerana (
<figureCitation box="[1287,1355,1274,1298]" captionStart="Fig. 3" captionStartId="5.[113,140,1315,1334]" captionTargetBox="[113,763,276,1300]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[113,763,276,1300]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. – Geographic distribution of Begueo onkeronensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (square), B. oustrolis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (diamond), B. betomponensis G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (triangle), B. golokensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry (star) and B. vulgoris G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry (circles), mapped on the bioclimatic zones of Madagascar (after CORNET, 1974; see SCHATZ, 2000)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888181/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
), which is included within the recently decreed Corridor Ankeniheny Zahamena PA. It can be easily distinguished from the two species most similar morphologically (
<taxonomicName box="[1258,1425,1370,1394]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="birtinshaaeii">
<emphasis box="[1258,1425,1370,1394]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">B. birkinshawii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[824,914,1402,1426]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Sapindaceae" genus="Beguea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="2" pageNumber="47" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="turtii">
<emphasis box="[824,914,1402,1426]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">B. turkii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by its leaflets with a long-acuminate apex and an acute acumen (vs acute to short acuminate apex and rounded to retuse acumen), short pedicels c. 1 mm long (vs 2.5-4 mm long), and large anthers 2.2-2.5 mm long (vs only 1 mm long) (
<figureCitation box="[832,893,1530,1554]" captionStart="Fig. 1" captionStartId="3.[113,140,1890,1909]" captionTargetBox="[320,1454,273,1842]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[320,1454,273,1842]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 1. – Begueo onkeronensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry. A. Flowering branch; B. Detail of flower at anthesis; C. Portion of inflorescence axis; D. Leaflet (lower surface); E. Leaflet (upper surface). [Antilohimeno 7978, MO] [Drawing: R. L. Andriamiarisoa]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/888179/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[906,920,1530,1554]" captionStart="Fig. 2" captionStartId="4.[136,163,1890,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[646,1477,276,973]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. – Photographs of Begueo Capuron. A. Begueo onkeronensis G. E. Schatz &amp; Lowry; B. Begueo opetolo Capuron; C. Begueo turkii G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry; D. Begueo vulgoris G. E. Schatz, Gereau &amp; Lowry." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1066560/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="47">2</figureCitation>
A).
</paragraph>
